 different from the resistance to entropy increase. Additionally, there is a distinction between sensory entropy (stemming from observational uncertainty) and physical entropy (stemming from physical disorder), even though they are quantified using the same formula. Free-energy theorists address this distinction by treating sensory processing as a transition through sensory states, relating the reduction of sensory entropy to the reduction of physical entropy.</p><p>Despite these difficulties, the second law of thermodynamics offers potential utility in conceptualizing free-energy minimization. It provides a new perspective, suggesting that minimizing free energy is fundamental to living agents either as a means of avoiding surprises and increasing survival or as a consequence of their existence.</p><p>In the context of the free-energy framework, active inference is introduced as a form of behavior where actions are taken to modify the environment and make it less surprising. Active inference allows agents to avoid surprises not only directly but also indirectly by changing the environment to fit their sensory predictions. This inversion of the traditional model of inference implies that inference can be an external activity affecting states of the world, not just an internal process.</p><p>To integrate active inference into the framework, an implementation mechanism is needed. Rather than requiring a full-fledged agent/environment simulation, free-energy theorists propose an arrangement in which the agent's current action is considered part of the environmental state. Actions and action sequences can be represented as predictions, and the objective becomes the minimization of predicted future surprise. This requires redefining the minimization criterion in terms of expected free energy.</p><p>In this arrangement, the agent and environment are representationally indivisible. The framework assumes the existence of two constructs: the R-density (probabilistic representation of what caused a sensation) and the G-density (the brain's beliefs about environmental causes of sensory input). The G-density can be seen as encoding the agent's beliefs or model of the environment. Notably, there is no independent representation of the environment; its state is defined by the agent's beliefs.</p><p>Fusing the agent and environment offers theoretical connections to approaches emphasizing extension, embodiment, and enaction, and it provides a natural way to capture goal-directed behavior. When agent and environment are fused, states of the world with high surprisal elicit actions that reduce the surprisal, leading to goal-directed behavior. However, this arrangement has conceptual drawbacks, such as circularity in suggesting that the agent takes actions according to its beliefs while also changing its beliefs based on its actions. The objective remains to improve predictability through the reduction of free energy, but now actions are understood to induce changes that the agent believes will eliminate the originally reduced free energy.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><d