s, it leads to increased surprise.</p><p>To reduce surprise, organisms engage in active inference. Active inference involves two complementary processes: perception and action. Perceptual processes aim to minimize surprise by adjusting internal models or beliefs to better match the sensory inputs. Action processes, on the other hand, involve modifying the environment to bring it more in line with the organism's predictions, thereby reducing surprise indirectly.</p><p>By minimizing surprise, organisms aim to maintain internal coherence and increase their understanding of the environment. This process allows them to make accurate predictions and take appropriate actions to ensure their survival and well-being. The avoidance of surprise can be seen as a fundamental principle governing cognitive behavior, shaping perception, decision-making, and action selection.</p><p>However, it's important to note that the role of surprise avoidance in the free-energy framework has faced some criticisms and challenges. Empirical evidence suggests that organisms do not always avoid surprises but, in certain cases, actively seek out surprising or novel experiences. This contradicts the strict prediction of surprise avoidance as a governing principle. Additionally, the circularity of the argument, where surprise avoidance is assumed to be beneficial because it is beneficial, raises questions about its explanatory power.</p><p>Overall, surprise avoidance plays a central role in the free-energy framework, driving organisms to minimize the discrepancy between their predictions and sensory inputs. However, the extent to which surprise avoidance accurately characterizes all aspects of cognitive behavior and its relationship to other cognitive processes requires further investigation and empirical evaluation.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:te