w biological systems, including the brain and cognition, function and adapt to their environment. It is based on the concept of free-energy, which can be understood as a measure of uncertainty or surprise.</p><p>Informally, the free-energy framework can be reconstructed as follows:</p><ol><li><p>Bayesian Inference: At its core, the framework relies on the principles of Bayesian inference. Bayesian inference is a process by which beliefs are updated based on new evidence. In the free-energy framework, this process is applied to perception and cognition, where the brain constantly makes predictions about the world and updates those predictions based on incoming sensory information.</p></li><li><p>Prediction Errors: In the free-energy framework, the brain's predictions are compared with the actual sensory inputs it receives. The mismatch between predictions and actual sensory inputs is referred to as prediction errors. Prediction errors signal a discrepancy between what was expected and what was actually observed.</p></li><li><p>Minimization of Free-Energy: The key idea in the free-energy framework is that biological systems, including the brain, strive to minimize free-energy. Free-energy is a measure of the discrepancy between the brain's predictions and the sensory inputs it receives. By minimizing free-energy, the system aims to reduce the surprise or uncertainty associated with prediction errors.</p></li><li><p>Active Inference: In order to minimize free-energy, the system engages in what is called active inference. Active inference involves both perception and action. The system not only updates its internal predictions based on sensory inputs but also takes actions to actively sample and gather new sensory information that can help reduce prediction errors.</p></li><li><p>Hierarchical Organization: The free-energy framework suggests that the brain is hierarchically organized. At higher levels of the hierarchy, more abstract predictions about the world are made, while at lower levels, more detailed sensory information is processed. The hierarchical structure allows for efficient processing and prediction generation.</p></li><li><p>Learning and Adaptation: The free-energy framework also accounts for learning and adaptation. The system learns from previous prediction errors and updates its internal models or beliefs to improve future predictions. This learning process helps the system become more attuned to the statistical regularities and patterns in the environment.</p></li></ol><p>Overall, the free-energy framework provides a theoretical account of how biological systems, such as the brain, perceive, learn, and adapt to their environment. By minimizing free-energy through active inference, the system aims to reduce surprise and uncertainty, making predictions that are in line with the observed sensory inputs. This framework has implications for understanding cognition, behavior, and the interactions between organisms and their environment.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 