ating internal models to better align with the regularities in the environment. By minimizing free-energy, the brain seeks to reduce prediction errors and improve the accuracy of its predictions. This is evident in skill acquisition, where initially novel and challenging tasks become more automatic and effortless with practice. Through repeated experience, the brain refines its predictions and minimizes surprise, leading to improved performance.</p></li><li><p>Emotion and Affective States: The free-energy framework can also be applied to emotions and affective states. Emotions can be seen as the brain's response to prediction errors that are particularly salient or significant. For example, a surprising event that deviates greatly from our predictions may elicit a strong emotional response. Emotion regulation involves minimizing free-energy by updating our predictions and reducing the impact of surprising events on our affective states.</p></li></ol><p>These examples demonstrate how the free-energy framework can be applied across various domains, from perception and action selection to learning and emotion. By framing these processes in terms of minimizing free-energy and resolving prediction errors, the framework offers a unified perspective on how biological systems interact with their environment and maintain adaptive behavior.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gra