namically favorable and can occur spontaneously. Conversely, if the change in free energy is positive, the process is thermodynamically forbidden or non-spontaneous without external energy input.</p><p>It's important to note that free energy is a relative quantity and depends on the choice of a reference point or zero energy state. This is because the free energy includes both the internal energy and the potential energy of the system. Therefore, only changes in free energy, rather than absolute values, have physical significance. By comparing the free energy of a system in different states or under different conditions, we can determine the thermodynamic favorability of processes and make predictions about their behavior.</p><p>The concept of free energy has broad applications in various branches of science and engineering, including chemistry, physics, biology, and materials science. It provides valuable insights into the energetics and stability of systems, helping us understand and manipulate their behavior.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-cen