l sensory inputs. The surprise-reduction hypothesis suggests that adaptive behavior can be understood as a process of reducing surprise or improbability.</p><p>However, the dark-room problem challenges the surprise-reduction hypothesis. It questions why organisms do not simply seek out unchanging and predictable environments if their goal is to minimize surprise. The article explores the tension between the need to reduce surprise and the presence of exploratory behavior in organisms.</p><p>The physicist in the conversation argues that the free-energy principle, which encompasses the minimization of free energy and surprise, is sufficient as a guiding principle for adaptive behavior. By minimizing surprise, organisms can adapt to a changing and uncertain world. The principle applies at different scales, from perception and learning to evolutionary adaptation.</p><p>The philosopher raises concerns about the circularity of the surprise-reduction hypothesis and the necessity of an appropriate interpretation or model of the world to calculate surprise. The absence of an adaptive interpretation leads to absurd behaviors, such as remaining in a dark room indefinitely. The conversation highlights the need for a larger explanatory package to address these issues.</p><p>The physicist argues that surprise reduction operates at multiple scales and involves modeling and anticipating a changing world. Organisms become optimal models of their environment through minimizing surprise, which aligns with the Good Regulator theorem. The existence of "dark-room agents" that can navigate specific environments like caves supports the idea that surprise reduction is tied to adaptive fitness.</p><p>In conclusion, the article presents a discussion on the free-energy principle, surprise reduction, and the dark-room problem. It explores the challenges and implications of the surprise-reduction hypothesis in understanding adaptive behavior and the role of modeling and perception in minimizing 