n prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert light"><p>Throughout our discussion, we have explored several topics related to the free-energy framework, surprisal, and the overloading of functions on the same hardware. Here is a final summary of the key points:</p><ol><li><p>Free-energy minimization: The free-energy framework proposes that biological systems are driven to minimize surprise or uncertainty by making predictions and updating their internal models based on sensory inputs. This principle applies to perception, cognition, learning, and behavior.</p></li><li><p>Surprisal: Surprisal is a measure of how surprising an outcome is based on its probability. Less probable outcomes have higher surprisal, while more probable outcomes have lower surprisal. Surprisal quantifies the amount of information gained from an outcome and is connected to information theory.</p></li><li><p>The dark-room problem: Critics of the free-energy framework raise the dark-room problem, which questions why biological systems engage in exploratory behaviors and do not simply avoid surprises by staying in unchanging environments. This highlights the tension between surprise-avoidance and the drive for exploration and adaptation.</p></li><li><p>Overloading of functions: The idea of overloading different functions on the same hardware refers to the ability of a system to perform multiple functions simultaneously. This design principle is observed in evolved and designed systems, where different functions coexist and interact within the same system or substrate.</p></li><li><p>Connections to Deleuze's multiple overlapping times: Deleuze's concept of multiple overlapping times shares similarities with the overloading of functions. Both emphasize multiplicity, non-linear time, rhizomatic structure, and the emergence of complexity. They challenge linear, hierarchical notions and provide a more dynamic and interconnected understanding of systems.</p></li></ol><p>In conclusion, the free-energy framework and surprisal offer insights into how biological systems minimize surprise and adapt to their environments. The overloading of functions on the same hardware and Deleuze's concept of multiple overlapping times provide alternative perspectives on complexity, non-linear time, and the interconnectedness of functions within systems. These ideas contribute to our understanding of cognition, behavior, and the design principles of evolved and designed systems.</p></div></div></div><div class="flex justify-between lg:block"><div class="text-xs flex items-center justify-center gap-1 self-center pt-2 !invisible"><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="15 18 9 12 15 6"></polyline></svg></button><span class="flex-grow flex-shrink-0">1 / 1</span><button disabled="" class="dark:text-white disabled:text-gray-300 dark:disabled:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="1.5" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-3 w-3" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><polyline points="9 18 15 12 9 6"></polyline></svg></button></div><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center mt-2 gap-2 md:gap-3 lg:gap-1 lg:absolute lg:top-0 lg:translate-x-full lg:right-0 lg:mt-0 lg:pl-2 visible"><button class="flex ml-auto gap-2 rounded-md p-1 hover:bg-gray-100 hover:text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-400 dark:hover:bg-gray-700 dark:hover:text-gray-200 disabled:dark:hover:text-gray-400"><svg stroke="currentColor" fill="none" stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="h-4 w-4" height="1em" width="1em" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M16 4h2a2 2 0 0 1 2 2v14a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H6a